2500|$|Many power {{supplies}} use {{more than one}} regulating method in series. For example, the output from a <b>switching</b> <b>regulator</b> can be further regulated by a linear regulator. The <b>switching</b> <b>regulator</b> accepts {{a wide range of}} input voltages and efficiently generates a (somewhat noisy) voltage slightly above the ultimately desired output. That is followed by a linear regulator that generates exactly the desired voltage and eliminates nearly all the noise generated by the <b>switching</b> <b>regulator.</b> Other designs may use an SCR regulator as the [...] "pre-regulator", followed by another type of regulator. An efficient way of creating a variable-voltage, accurate output power supply is to combine a multi-tapped transformer with an adjustable linear post-regulator.|$|E
